Project Goals¶

For our final project, we, Disha Amin and Martina Vasconez, will collaborate to explore the chemicals commonly found in the beauty and cosmetic industry. We aim to analyze how these chemicals are priced and their potential effects on human health.

Our hypothesis is if certain beauty products are priced higher, then the chemicals in them should cause fewer bodily irritations and other related health problems because expensive products give consumers the impression that they are better for human bodies.

To support our analysis, we will gather data from relevant datasets that illustrate the relationships between product pricing, chemical composition, and associated health impacts.

To ensure efficiency and effective teamwork in our project, we have established a comprehensive collaboration plan.

  • Weekly Meetings: We plan to meet once a week in the afternoons, or more frequently if needed, to discuss project progress, share updates, and address any challenges we may face.

  • Communication: We have exchanged contact information to facilitate ongoing communication. This will enable us to quickly discuss ideas, ask questions, or resolve issues that may arise.

  • Remote Collaboration: We have created a shared document and a Google Colab notebook that facilitate remote collaboration. The document will serve as a central location for notes, project outlines, and any research findings we gather outside of our scheduled meetings. Meanwhile, the Google Colab notebook will be dedicated to coding.

By adhering to this collaboration plan, we aim to maintain clear communication and ensure that all aspects of our project are completed efficiently and effectively.

Key Datasets for Investigation¶

Our analysis utilizes two primary datasets that address key aspects of our exploration into cosmetic chemicals and their implications for human health:

Cosmetics Database: This dataset provides comprehensive information about various cosmetic companies, their products (categorized by type), ingredients, and prices. It serves as the basis for analyzing price distributions, ingredient compositions, and trends among different product categories. Through this dataset, we can explore questions such as:

  • Which products contain specific chemicals?
  • How are prices distributed across brands and product types?
  • Are higher-priced products associated with specific ingredients or categories?

ECHA Europa C & L Inventory: This dataset is sourced from ECHA Europa and focuses on the hazard classifications of individual chemicals. Each chemical is linked to a unique CAS Number and is categorized based on hazard notifications from companies and manufacturers. This dataset enables us to investigate the health implications of cosmetic ingredients by analyzing:

  • The frequency and severity of hazard notifications.
  • Patterns between chemical hazards and product pricing.
  • Specific hazard codes related to skin, eye, respiratory irritation, and environmental toxicity.

By integrating these datasets, we can uncover relationships between product price, chemical composition, and health hazards, laying the groundwork for our predictive models and further analyses.

Data Exploration and ETL¶

We began our analysis with the cosmetics dataset to gain insights into the beauty industry. This dataset consists of 11 columns, including Label, Brand, Price, and Name. Our initial focus will be on exploring this dataset in depth to provide context and understand its structure. Through this analysis, we aim to derive insights into various aspects of cosmetics, such as price distribution, product rankings, and other relevant trends.

Then, we expanded our investigation by exploring different chemicals depending on price ranges. This approach allowed us to integrate the cosmetics data with hazard data from the ECHA Europa database, enabling a deeper analysis of relationships between product characteristics, chemical compositions, and associated health hazards.

To adhere to tidy data principles, we will create two separate datasets, ensuring that each entity has its own table. One table will contain product information, while the other will focus on ingredients. These tables will be interconnected by a unique Product ID, allowing for efficient data analysis and retrieval.

Relationship between Price and Rank¶

Now, let's explore whether there is any relationship between a product's price and its rank. Understanding this correlation can help us determine if higher-priced products tend to be rated more favorably or if rank and price are independent of one another. By visualizing this relationship, we can uncover potential trends or patterns that might inform our further analysis.

Correlation Between Price and Rank: -0.025214717679718862

This scatter plot illustrates the relationship between two key variables in our dataset: price and rank. Interestingly, the graphic suggests that higher prices are associated with lower product ranks.

The correlation coefficient calculated between these two variables is -0.025, indicating a very weak negative relationship. This means that there is almost no linear correlation between price and rank, suggesting that variations in price do not significantly influence product rankings.

To deepen our understanding of this relationship, it would be beneficial to have documentation outlining the factors that contribute to a product's rank in the original dataset. Having such information could clarify whether certain price ranges are systematically associated with specific qualities or attributes that influence consumer ratings. Without the information, we can only assume that products tend to be ranked higher when they are cheaper because consumers gravitite towards affordable prices.

Overall, while our initial hypothesis suggested a potential positive correlation between higher prices and better rankings, the data indicates that this may not hold true in this context, highlighting the complexity of consumer preferences in the beauty and cosmetic industry.

Categorizing Ingredients by Average Price Percentiles¶

To investigate the relationship between ingredient price and safety, we categorized ingredients into four distinct groups based on their average price: lowest, 25th percentile, median (50th percentile), and highest. This systematic categorization allows us to explore trends across price ranges.

  • For the lowest percentile, we identified ingredients with the exact minimum price.
  • For the 25th and median percentiles, we selected the top 10 ingredients closest to these values.
  • For the highest category, we highlighted the top 10 ingredients with the greatest average prices, representing the premium end of the spectrum.

This categorization provides a structured framework to compare ingredients across price tiers and investigate whether higher-priced ingredients are associated with fewer or different health hazards.

In [248]:
# Calculate percentiles
percentiles = {
    "Lowest (0th Percentile)": grouped.min(),
    "25th Percentile": grouped.quantile(0.25),
    "Median (50th Percentile)": grouped.median(),
}

# Top 10 highest prices
top_10_highest = grouped.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)

# Add these to the categorization for display
categorized_ingredients = {}
for category, value in percentiles.items():
    if category in ["25th Percentile", "Median (50th Percentile)"]:
        ingredients = grouped[abs(grouped - value) < 0.01].sort_values(ascending=False).head(10)
    else:
        ingredients = grouped[grouped == value]
    categorized_ingredients[category] = ingredients

categorized_ingredients["Highest"] = top_10_highest

# Display the results
print("\n--- Price Analysis of Ingredients by Percentiles ---\n")
for category, ingredients in categorized_ingredients.items():
    print(f"{category} - Average Price:")
    if not ingredients.empty:
        for ingredient, price in ingredients.items():
            print(f"  {ingredient}: ${price:.2f}")
    else:
        print("No ingredients found in this category.")
    print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

Fetching Hazard Data from ECHA Europa¶

To analyze the selected chemicals, we utilized the ECHA Europa database to extract their hazard data. Using a custom-built function, we scraped the ECHA Europa website for the hazard information of each chemical, organized the data into a dictionary of URLs, and subsequently processed it into a consolidated DataFrame. This allowed us to generate heat maps to visualize the distribution and severity of hazards across different chemicals.

Hazard Data for Lowest Price Chemicals¶

In [249]:
# Function to fetch and clean data from a given URL
def fetch_and_clean_chemical_data(url):
    try:
        response = requests.get(url, timeout=10)
        response.raise_for_status()

        # Parse the HTML content
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.content, 'html.parser')
        html_tables = str(soup.find_all("table"))
        df = pd.read_html(StringIO(html_tables))[1]  # Select the relevant table

        # Clean the dataset
        df.columns = df.columns.droplevel(0)
        columns_to_drop = [
            "Supplementary Hazard Statement Code(s)",
            "Specific Concentration limits, M-Factors",
            "Notes",
            "Classification affected by Impurities / Additives",
            "Joint Entries",
            "Unnamed: 11_level_1"
        ]
        df = df.drop(columns=columns_to_drop, errors='ignore')  # Ignore errors if columns are missing
        df.columns = [
            "Hazard Class and Category Code(s)",
            "Hazard Statement Code(s)",
            "Hazard Statement Code(s), Extended",
            "Pictograms, Signal Word Code(s)",
            "Additional Notified Information",
            "Number of Notifiers"
        ]
        return df
    except:
        return None

# Dictionary of chemicals
lowest_price_chemicals = {
    "Denatonium Benzoate": 'https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/cl-inventory-database/-/discli/details/17558',
    "Hamamelis Virginiana": 'https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/cl-inventory-database/-/discli/details/14742',
    "Rosa Centifolia Flower Extract": 'https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/cl-inventory-database/-/discli/details/9565',
    "Sodium Saccharin": 'https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/cl-inventory-database/-/discli/details/18951',
    "Vinyl Caprolactam/VP/Dimethylaminoethyl Methacrylate Copolymer": 'https://echa.europa.eu/information-on-chemicals/cl-inventory-database/-/discli/details/210929'

}

# Fetch and Combine Data
lowest_price_data = []

for chemical, url in lowest_price_chemicals.items():
    df = fetch_and_clean_chemical_data(url)
    if df is not None:
        df["Chemical"] = chemical
        lowest_price_data.append(df)

# Combine all data
if lowest_price_data:
    combined_lowest_df = pd.concat(lowest_price_data, ignore_index=True)
    combined_lowest_df["Hazard Statement Code(s)"] = combined_lowest_df["Hazard Statement Code(s)"].str.slice(0, 4)

    # Aggregate Hazard Data
    hazard_summary = combined_lowest_df.pivot_table(
        index="Hazard Statement Code(s)",
        columns="Chemical",
        values="Number of Notifiers",
        aggfunc="sum",
        fill_value=0
    )

    # Display the summary pivot table
    print("\n--- Hazard Summary for Lowest Price Chemicals ---")
    display(hazard_summary)

    # Heatmap to visualize hazards across chemicals
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 7))
    sns.heatmap(hazard_summary, annot=True, fmt="d", cmap="coolwarm", cbar_kws={'label': 'Number of Notifiers'})
    plt.title("Hazard Statements for Lowest Price Chemicals", fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel("Chemical")
    plt.ylabel("Hazard Statement Codes")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Comparing Hazard Distributions Across Price Categories¶

In this section, we compare the aggregated hazard notifications across the four price categories: Lowest Price, 25th Percentile, Median Price, and Highest Price. By summarizing and visualizing the hazard distributions for each category, we aim to identify trends and differences in chemical risks associated with varying price ranges. This analysis provides a comprehensive view of how price correlates with potential health hazards, enabling a deeper understanding of the relationship between product cost and safety.

In [253]:
# Aggregate hazard data for each category
categories = {
    "Lowest Price": combined_lowest_df,
    "25th Percentile": combined_q25_df,
    "Median Price": combined_med_df,
    "Highest Price": combined_high_df
}

# Initialize an empty DataFrame
hazard_summary_all = pd.DataFrame()

# Process each category
for category, df in categories.items():
    aggregated = df.pivot_table(
        index="Hazard Statement Code(s)",
        values="Number of Notifiers",
        aggfunc="sum",
        fill_value=0
    )
    # Sum across all chemicals
    hazard_summary_all[category] = aggregated.sum(axis=1)

hazard_summary_all.index = hazard_summary_all.index.str.slice(0, 4)

# Plot the stacked bar chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
hazard_summary_all.T.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(8, 7), colormap="viridis")
plt.title("Comparison of Hazard Distributions Across Price Categories", fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel("Number of Notifiers", fontsize=12)
plt.xlabel("Price Categories", fontsize=12)
plt.xticks(rotation=45, fontsize=10)

plt.legend(
    title="Hazard Statement Codes",
    title_fontsize=10,
    fontsize=9,
    loc='upper right',
    ncol=4
)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

<Figure size 1200x800 with 0 Axes>

The stacked bar chart reveals a clear trend in hazard distributions across price categories. The 25th Percentile category has the highest total number of hazard notifications, surpassing even the Lowest Price category, suggesting that some mid-priced products may rely on more hazardous ingredients. Lower-priced products also show significant hazard diversity, with common hazards like "H302" (harmful if swallowed) and "H412" (harmful to aquatic life). In contrast, Median and Highest Price categories have fewer notifiers and a narrower range of hazards, supporting the hypothesis that higher-priced products may prioritize safer ingredients. However, even high-priced products are not entirely free of hazards. These results indicate a general trend of lower hazards in higher-priced products but highlight exceptions, particularly in the 25th Percentile category, warranting further investigation.

Modeling Ideas for Future Analysis¶

Based on our exploratory data analysis, we propose two plausible models to build using our data:

1. Predicting Hazard Severity Based on Price and Chemical Composition This model aims to predict the likelihood or severity of health hazards associated with a cosmetic product. The dependent variable will be the hazard severity, represented by the frequency of hazard statement codes (e.g., H302, H319, H412). The independent variables will include:

  • The average price of the product or ingredient.
  • The presence of specific high-risk chemicals (Denatonium Benzoate, Rosa Damascena Flower Extract, etc.).
  • The product type (moisturizer, cleanser, etc.).

Using a classification model we can categorize hazard severity into levels (low, medium, high, etc.). Alternatively, a regression model could be used to predict the total number of hazard notifications for a given product. This model will help determine if price and chemical composition are reliable predictors of potential health risks.

2. Analyzing the Relationship Between Hazard Types and Product Ratings This model will investigate whether the type and frequency of hazards associated with a product correlate with consumer ratings. The dependent variable will be the product rating, while the independent variables will include:

  • Grouped hazard categories (skin-related hazards such as H315, H318; respiratory hazards such as H335 or environmental hazards such as H412).
  • Product price category (lowest price, 25th percentile, median, highest price).

Using linear regression or correlation analysis, we can identify patterns in how different types of hazards impact consumer perceptions of product quality. This will provide insights into whether safety concerns influence consumer behavior or whether other factors dominate consumer preferences.

These models will allow us to investigate critical questions about the trade-offs between product affordability, chemical safety, and consumer perception. They also provide a foundation for actionable recommendations in the cosmetic industry, such as pricing strategies or ingredient transparency.
